{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=FV ''Jutland''}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image= }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country=[[Canada]] |Ship flag=[[File:Canadian Red Ensign 1921-1957.svg|60px|Canada]] |Ship name="Jutland" |Ship namesake= |Ship owner=LaHave Fishing Company |Ship operator= |Ship route= |Ship ordered= |Ship builder=Boehner Bros. |Ship yard number= |Ship way number= |Ship laid down= |Ship launched=1918 |Ship completed= |Ship christened= |Ship acquired= |Ship maiden voyage= |Ship out of service= |Ship registry=[[LaHave, Nova Scotia]] |Ship identification= | Ship fate = Missing as of March 10, 1920| Ship status = Unknown | Ship notes= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class= |Ship tonnage=136 tons<ref>[https://novascotia.ca/museum/wrecks/wrecks/shipwrecks.asp?ID=2554 Marine Heritage Database: Jutland - 1920] Maritime Museum of the Atlantic</ref> |Ship displacement= |Ship length= {{convert|135|ft|abbr=on}} |Ship beam= |Ship height= |Ship draught= |Ship draft= |Ship depth= |Ship decks= |Ship ice class= |Ship sail plan=[[Fishing trawler#beam trawlers|Beam trawler]] |Ship power= |Ship propulsion= |Ship speed= |Ship capacity= |Ship crew= |Ship notes= }} |}
'''''Jutland''''' was a Canadian [[Fishing trawler#beam trawlers|beam trawler]] based out of [[Liverpool, Nova Scotia]]. Built in 1918 by the Boehner Bros., she was owned by LaHave Fishing Company.<ref>[http://www.shipbuildinghistory.com/history/canadayards/otherns.htm Other Boatbuilders in Nova Scotia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016004102/http://www.shipbuildinghistory.com/history/canadayards/otherns.htm# |date=2014-10-16 }} Shipbuildinghistory.com</ref><ref>[http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?34777 MV Jutland (+1920)] Wrecksite.eu</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|url=http://www.novanewsnow.com/Business/2008-02-04/article-595947/The-Beam-Trawler-Jutland/1 |title= The Beam Trawler "Jutland" |newspaper=Nova News Now|location=Liverpool, Nova Scotia|date=February 4, 2008}}</ref>
==Disappearance== On March 10, 1920, ''Jutland'' left [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], [[Nova Scotia]], with a crew of 21 heading to the Western Bank fishing grounds.<ref name="Chronicle">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Fear Beam Trawler Jutland Lost With All On Board |newspaper=Chronicle Herald|location=Halifax, Nova Scotia|date=March 13, 1920 |page=1}}</ref> On the morning of March 11, the Halifax steam trawler ''Lemberg'' discovered two [[Dory|dories]] approximately 160 kilometers (86 nautical miles) southeast of Halifax.<ref name="Chronicle"/><ref name="CFA">{{cite book |last= |first= |date= March 1920|title=The Canadian Fisherman |url=https://archive.org/details/canadianfisherma07cana |dead-url= |location=Gardenvale, Quebec|publisher=National Business Publications |page=54 |isbn= |archive-url= |archive-date=July 14, 1920}}</ref> Both dories were damaged and full of water.<ref name="Chronicle"/> The body of John R. Ellison, a mate of ''Jutland'', was discovered aboard one of the dories.<ref name="Chronicle"/><ref name="CFA"/> The bodies of the 20 other crew members were never found.<ref name="Chronicle"/> Various theories on what happened to ''Jutland'' have been examined, from an explosion to a collision.<ref name="Chronicle"/>
