{{lead rewrite|date=October 2018}}
'''Stolist''' is a term used to describe something within the culture of [[ancient Egypt]].

The stolist was a person participating within the society of ancient Egypt who held the rank of [[priest]], and whom we understand to have been an adorner of divine images. At some time stolists belonged to a group or guild known as ''nekrostolisteis'', as is attested to by the [[archaeology|archaeological]] finds of the [[Siwa Oasis]], this particularly being an inscription dating to the [[1st century]] C.E.<ref>D. Frankfurter - [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Y6VJgeU28lQC&pg=PA73&dq=stolist&hl=en&sa=X&ei=1DqRVauvOaLP7ga5pYHQAQ&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=stolist&f=false Religion in Roman Egypt: Assimilation and Resistance (p.73)] Princeton University Press 1998 (reprint), 314 pages, ''Mythos: the Princeton/Bollingen Series in World Mythology Series'', {{ISBN|0691070547}} [Retrieved 2015-06-29]</ref>

